      • getEvLevel

        public short getEvLevel()
        Get Level Event Information. Level status information The tilt sensor generates events if the status has changed. The number outputted corresponds to the identifier "75" with the exception of the number "0".
        EvLev:
        1 … The tilt plane was redetermined and is identical to the previous measurement.
        2 … The tilt plane is "old" but can currently not be determined (system overload).
        3 … The tilt plane was redetermined but it has changed.
        4 … The tilt plane could not yet be determined (after power up, level enabled)
        5 … The tilt plane is/was deactivated (level disabled)
        6 … The tilt measurement is unstable (measured value is changing continuously -> vibrations etc.)
        Example: EvLev: 1
        Returns:
        status

      • getEvPosMotor

        public java.lang.String getEvPosMotor()
        Get Motor stopped in position - Motor This signals that a turning motor has stopped because it has either reached the intended position or for another reason (error situation) or has been prematurely stopped by the user "ps" (position top).
        An individual event is triggered for each motor. The commands "pa", "pr" and "cf" always generate events for both motors even if only one motor was supposed to have started (e.g. pa 22:4.7).
        The command "ps" also generates an event if the relevant motor or motors are stopped at this moment in time. If the commands "pa", "pr" or "cf" are interrupted with "ps", then only one event per motor is generated. This event indicates only that the moving motor has come to a stop, irrespective of whether it has reached the intended position or has been prematurely stopped by the "ps" command. "ps H" and "ps V" trigger the respective corresponding event, "ps B" generates events for both motors. If an error occurs with a motor, then an error message is output.
        EvPos: ( | )
        [V, H] V … Vertical motor, H … Horizontal motor
        Example:
        EvPos : V ! EvPos : V @E3154
        EvPos: H ! EvPos: H @E2154
        Returns:
        Value

      • getEvKeyKey

        public int getEvKeyKey()
        Get Remote Control - key (pad).
        * Pressing a key on the remote control generates the "event"(Key down). When the key is released, another "Event" (Key up) is sent. The key code is transmitted along with both events.
        EvKey:
        [0..31] Key code
        [d,u] d … "Key down", u … "Key up"
        Example:
        EvKey: 1d Key 1 down
        EvKey: 1u Key 1 up
        Returns:
        Key Value

      • getEvLineBattery

        public java.lang.String getEvLineBattery()
        Get Information about Battery.
        An event is generated when the external voltage supply is connected or disconnected. If the rechargeable battery voltage falls below a lower limit (battery almost empty), an event is likewise triggered. At any time after this occurs, the device can switch itself off (to protect the rechargeable batteries) without warning.
        EvLine:
        con. External voltage supply connected
        dis. External voltage supply disconnected/interrupted
        EvBat:
        empty Battery is empty -> Device switches itself off soon after this
        Example:
        EvLine: con. EvLine: dis. EvBat: empty
        Returns:
        when empty

      • getEvMsgAction

        public java.lang.String getEvMsgAction()
        Get System Errors or warnings.
        System errors or warnings are indicated by the red LED. IDs 60 and 61 (16Bit variable) supply information about the causes. Each variable can store 16 states. The setting or deletion of the individual Bits is signalled by this "event". The event supplies information if the state of one of the individual Bits changes. IDs 60 and 61 supply all the information about all the Bits (decimal number).
        EvMsg:
        [s, c] s.. set (Bit), c .. clear (Bit)
        [F, W] F.. fault (system error), W .. warning
        [0 .. 15] Bit (Flag)
        Example:
        EvMsg: sW 1 (The device is tilted too much -> Bit 1 set -> "get: 61:2“)
        EvMsg: cW 1 (The device is correctly set up again -> Bit 1 set -> "get: 61:0“)
        Returns:
        action

      • getEvCalResult

        public java.lang.String getEvCalResult()
        This signals that the initiated self-calibration sequence has been ended. The feedback about success or failure is indicated by the parameters following the event name. If the calibration is successful, this is signalled by an "!". If it was a failure, the cause of the error is indicated in the error code "@EXXXX".

        EvCal: ( | )
        Example:
        EvCal: ! (Calibration successfully completed)
        EvCal: @E0798 (Calibration (in this case: compensator) ended because the device was moving)
        Returns:
        result
